Navigate to https://www.hyrtutorials.com/p/waits-demo.html. Write a program to click "Add Textbox1" and check that the button got disabled or not after 5secs.

package selepractice;

import org.openqa.selenium.chrome.ChromeDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.ExpectedCondition;
import org.openqa.selenium.support.ui.WebDriverWait;
import java.time.Duration;
import org.openqa.selenium.By;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebDriver;
import org.openqa.selenium.WebElement;

public class Synchronization_buttonDisable {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		
		WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();
		String url = "https://www.hyrtutorials.com/p/waits-demo.html";
		String id = "btn1";
		driver.get(url);
		
		WebElement button1, text1;
		driver.manage().window().maximize();
		
		button1 = driver.findElement(By.id("btn1"));
		button1.click();
		
		//To print the text
		System.out.println("Clicked Text Box1");
		
		WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(5));

		
		boolean isDisabled = wait.until(new ExpectedCondition <Boolean> () {
			public Boolean apply (WebDriver driver) {
				return !driver.findElement(By.id(id)).isEnabled();
			}	
		});
		
		if (isDisabled) {
            System.out.println("Button became disabled within 5 seconds.");
        } else {
            System.out.println("Button did NOT become disabled within 5 seconds.");
        }
		}
}

Explain the difference between Wait and Thread.sleep()
Both wait() and Thread.sleep() are used to pause the execution of a thread, but they are used for different purposes and behave differently.
1. Definition-
- wait() is a method of the object class and is used for inter-thread communication.
- Thread.sleep() is a method the Thread class and is used to pause a thread for a fixed time.
2. Lock Handling-
- wait() releases the lock(monito) on the object when it is called.
- Thread.sleep() does not release any lock the thread is holding.
3. Usage context-
- wait() must be called inside  synchronized block or method.
- Thread.sleep() can be called from anywhere and does not require synchronization.
4. Waking up the Thread-
- A thread in wait() state is awakened by calling notify() or notifyAll() on the same object.
- A thread in Thread.sleep() wakes up automatically after the specified time.
5. Purpose-
- wait() is used when threads need to communicate or coordinate with each other.
- Thread.sleep() is mainly used to introduce a delay in execution.
6. Exceptions-
- Both methods throw InterruptedException, which must be handled using tryâ€“catch or declared with throws.

	
